Jupiter punishes humanity with a flood
Deucalion and Pyrrha survive and repopulate the earth by throwing the &lsquo;bones of the mother&rsquo; (the rocks) behind them
They must not look behind them while they do this Apollo speaks disparagingly to Cupid who shoots arrows to retaliate
First arrow causes Apollo to fall in love Second arrow makes Daphne (the object of love) to flee Daphne rejects him Daphne calls out to father for help-who turns her into a tree Jupiter rapes Io and turns her into a cow to prevent his wife Juno from catching on
&gt; “Nature displayed a single aspect only,throughout the cosmos; Chaos, was its name,a shapeless, unwrought mass of inert bulk. (8-10) Some god (of kinder nature) settled this dispute by separating earth from heaven, and then by separating sea from earth and fluid aether from the denser air; and after these were separated out.(26-30)”&gt; “Heat makes the middle zone unlivable, and the two outer zones are deep in snow; between these two extremes, he placed two others of temperate climate, blending cold and warmth. (68-71) now man was born, either because the framer of all things, the fabricator of this better world created man out of his own divine substance--or else because Prometheus took up a clod ...... molded it into the shape of gods, who govern all. (108-117)”The Golden Age# &ldquo;men had no fear of any punishment, nor did they read of threatened penalties engraved in bronze (129-31) No rake had been familiar with the earth (141) As yet no pine tree on its mountaintop had been chopped down and fitted out to ship. (134-35)&rdquo;
The Silver Age# &ldquo;When Saturn was dispatched to Tartarus, Jove ruled the world. (155-56) Jupiter made the ancient springtime shorter by adding onto it three seasons more: now winter, summer, an erratic fall, and a brief spring filled out the fourfold year. (158-61)&rdquo;
The Bronze Age# &ldquo;crueler by nature and much more disposed, to savage warfare, but not yet corrupt (170-71)&rdquo;
The Iron Age# &ldquo;all forms of evil burst upon this time (173) Now ships spread sail, though sailors until now knew nothing of them; pines that formerly had stood upon the summits of their mountains, turned into keels. (178-81)&rdquo;
War with the Giants# &ldquo;the race of Giants plotted (we hear) to rule in heaven by themselves: they brought together mountains in a heap and piled them up to reach the lofty stars; then the omnipotent father launched a bolt that shattered Mount Olympus at the base, so Pelion came crashing down from Ossa. (205-12)&rdquo;
Lyacon# &ldquo;Gods take this path to the royal apartments of Jove the Thunderer; on either side are palaces with folding doors flung wide, and filled with guests of their distinguished owners. (232-35)&rdquo;
&ldquo;The age&rsquo;s infamy had reached our ears; hoping to disprove it, | glided down from the summit of Olympus, concealing my godhood in a human form, and walked upon the earth. (293-97) By signs | let them know a god had come, and common folk began to offer prayers; at first Lycaon mocked their piety (306-8) He planned to take me, overcome with sleep, and murder me as | lay unawares; that was his way of getting at the truth. (312-14)&rdquo;
The Flood# &ldquo;Neptune, his sky-blue brother, aids him with waves of fresh auxiliaries. The tyrant calls his rivers to assemble beneath his roof&hellip; (381-84) Now unrestrained, the sea conceals the hills, and strange new waves beat at the mountaintops; the greater part are drowned beneath the waves, while those spared drowning perish of starvation. (328)&rdquo;
Deuclaion and Pyrrha# &ldquo;There Mount Parnassus raises its twin peaks, piercing the clouds and seeking out the stars; in this place (which alone was unsubmerged) Deucalion, and she who shared his bed, borne on a little raft, had come to land. (436-440) Go from my temple now, with your heads covered and your robes unbound; behind you, toss the bones of your great mother! (527-29)&rdquo;
Second Creation# &ldquo;So when the earth, still completely covered with fresh muck from that just receded flood, was heated by the sun&rsquo;s rays, she produced countless species; some were the old ones, restored, and others were monsters, novel in their shapes. (602-6) Unwillingly, the earth bore you, as well, enormous Python, serpent quite unknown to all prior ages—you, who would become a terror to the newly fashioned folks, so very like a mountainside you were; (607-11)&rdquo;
Apollo and Daphne# &quot; What are you doing with such manly arms, lascivious boy? That bow befits our brawn, wherewith we deal out wounds to savage beasts and other mortal foes, unerringly. (634-37) Your arrow, Phoebus, may strike everything; mine will strike you: as animals to gods, your glory is so much the less than mine! (644-46)&quot;
&ldquo;i Cupid struck Peneus&rsquo; daughter [Daphne], while the other pierced Apollo to his marrow (655-56) One is in love now, and the other one won&rsquo;t hear of it, for Daphne calls it joy to roam within the forest&rsquo;s deep seclusion, where she, in emulation of the chaste goddess Phoebe [Diana], devotes herself to hunting. (657-61) Alas, there is no herbal remedy for the love that | must suffer, and the arts that heal all others cannot heal their lord— (723-25)&rdquo;
Hunting metaphors increasingly common
&ldquo;Help me, dear father! If your waters hold divinity, transform me and destroy that beauty by which | have too well pleased! (751-53) her supple trunk is girdled with a thing layer of fine bark over her smooth skin; her hair turns into foliage, her arms grow branches, sluggish roots adhere to feet that were so recently swift, her head becomes the summit of a tree; all that remains of her is a warm glow. (756-62)&rdquo;
Jove and Io/Jove# &ldquo;Ovid&rsquo;s seamless links Here is the house, the seat, the inner chambers of the great river; here Peneus holds court [the father of Daphne] in his rocky cavern and lays down the law to water nymphs and tributary streams. (793-96) Inachus was the only river absent, concealed in the recesses of his cave he added to his volume with tears he grimly wept for his lost daughter lo. (806-9)&rdquo;
&ldquo;| am he who hurls the roaming thunderbolt— don&rsquo;t run from me! But run she did, through Lerna and Lyrcea, until the god concealed the land entirely beneath a dense dark mist and seized her and dishonored here. (828-32) Juno, however, happened to look down on Argos, where she noticed something odd: swift-flying clouds had turned day into night (833-35)&rdquo;
&ldquo;Having intuited his wife&rsquo;s approach, Jove had already metamorphosed lo into a gleaming heifer—a beauty still even as a COW. (846-49) Jove, lying to forestall all inquiries as to her origin and pedigree, replied that she was born out of the earth. Then Juno asked him for her as a gift. (853-56)&rdquo;
&ldquo;Juno feared Jove had more such tricks in mind, and couldn&rsquo;t feel entirely secure until she&rsquo;d placed this heifer in the care of Argus, the watchman with a hundred eyes. (866-69) and when she tried to utter a complaint she only mooed—a sound which terrified her, fearful as she now was of her own voice. (883-85) but with her hoof, she drew lines in the dust, and letters of the words she could not speak told the sad story of her transformation. (899-901)&rdquo;
Stories within stories# &ldquo;Argus, struggling to stay awake: even though Slumber closes down some eyes, others stay vigilant. Argus inquired how the reed pipes, so recently invented, had come to be, and Mercury responded. (949-52) the god [Pan], assuming that he had captured Syrinx, grasped instead a handful of marsh reeds! and while he sighed, the reeds in his hands, stirred by his own breath, gave forth a similar, low-pitched complaint! (974-78)&rdquo;
&ldquo;O Argus, you are fallen, and the light in all your lamps is utterly put out: one hundred eyes, one darkness all the same! (995-97) The goddess was now pacified, and lo at once began regaining her lost looks, till she became what she had been before; (1020-22)&rdquo;
Phaethon (as link too book 2)# &ldquo;Her son, Epaphus, is believed to be sprung from the potent seed of mighty Jove, and temples may be found in every city wherein the boy is honored with his parent. He had a friend, like him in age and spirit, named Phaethon, the sun god&rsquo;s child. One day this boy was boasting, and in vanity would not take second place to Epaphus, so proud he as that Phoebus was his father. (1034-39)&rdquo;
Book 2# Summary# Phaeton travels to the palace of the sun to locate his father Artwork on palace doors depicts sea, land heavens The sun is Phaetons father Wants to drive his fathers chariot and horses Dad tries to convince him that it is impossible to do Does it anyway He is not able to control it The sun is to close to the earth Earth suffers as he gets closer Jupiter kills him because the chaos that he is causing His sisters are transformed into amber trees because of their grief over death of their brother Jupiter rapes calypso Juno turns Calisto into a bear Arcas almost kills mother (as a bear) and to save this Jupiter converts them into a constellation Description of conversation between raven and a crow Crow was a beautiful princess Loyalty does not pay off Raven reports Coronis&rsquo;s infidelity to Apollo, who is outraged and kills him with an arrow Punishes the raven and turns it into a black bird from a white one Apollo saves the baby inside of Chronis&rsquo;s womb and entrusts it to Chiron Mercury steals Apollos flock Here (Athenian Maiden) steals his heart Minerva angry with Aglauros and fills him with envy Mercury fails to win Herse Start of Book 2# &ldquo;There stood the regal palace of the Sun, soaring upon its many lofty columns, with roof of gold and fire-flashing bronze, and ceilings intricate with ivory, and double-folding doors that shone with silver. (1-5) Soon as the son of Clymene had climbed the steep path leading to the dwelling place of his reputed parent, he went in and turned at once to meet his father&rsquo;s gaze— though at some distance, for he could not bear such brightness any closer. (24-29)&rdquo;
&ldquo;in attendance on his léff@hd right stood Day and Month and Year and Century, and all the Hours, evenly divided; fresh Spring was there, adorned with floral crown, and Summer, naked, bearing ripened grain, and Autumn, stained from treading out her grapes, and Winter with his gray and frosty locks. And sitting in the middle of these figures, the all-seeing Sun looked upon the youth, who quaked with terror at such novel sights. (32-41)&rdquo;
&ldquo;You seek a gift that is too great for you, beyond your strength, beyond your boyish years. Out of your ignorance, you seek much more than even gods are able to control, for though each god may do just as he pleases, none but myself may set his heel upon the fire-bearing axle. No—not even he who governs vast Olympus&hellip; when | look down on the earth and seas, fear often makes me tremble, and the heart within my breast is seized with palpitations! (73-74, 76-81, 89-90)&rdquo;
&ldquo;Perhaps you think that there are sacred groves and cities of the gods along the way, temples displaying all the gifts of wealth? Not so: your path is full of lurking perils as well as images of savage beasts. And if you hold this course unswervingly, you&rsquo;ll find the horns of Taurus in your way, the Archer and the gaping jaws of Leo, and Scorpio, whose long and curving arms sweep one away, while the curving arms of Cancer sweep broadly in the opposite direction. (104-14)&rdquo;
&ldquo;But his rebellious son refused to listen and adamantly kep to his design. (142-43) For the first time, then, the Great and Little Bears knew the sun&rsquo;s heat and tried—in vain, for it was not permitted— to plunge into the sea. (229-32) Athos burns, Cilician Taurus and Timolus burn, and Oeta, too; Mount Ida, which had once been full of fountains, now runs dry and burns; Muse-haunted Helicon and Haemus (not yet associated with Oeagrus); Etna (already blazing) blazes twice. (289-95)&rdquo; &ldquo;Now terrified, it is impossible for him to use the reins that he was given. (226-27) no solution to his problem may be found, and stunned by ignorance, cannot decide if he should hold the reins or let them go— he doesn&rsquo;t even know his horses&rsquo; names! (257-61)&rdquo;
&ldquo;Before he would commit himself, however, the father almighty made the other gods (especially the god who gave his son the chariot) swear that the gravest fate hung over all, unless he should take action. And then he sought the pinnacle of heaven, whence he was wont to parcel out the rain clouds widely over the earth, and whence he moved the thunder and sent forth his lightning bolts. and so he thundered and released a bolt of lightning from beside his ear that drove the hapless driver from his spinning wheels and from his life: fires put cruel fires out. (402-10, 413-16)&rdquo;
