Turned into frankincense Alcithoe tells love story
Salmacis desires Hermaphroditus Venus&rsquo;s request transforms Ino and child into sea deities Meet Peruses
Stops in Atlas&rsquo;s kingdom Will plunder riches No match for Atlas but uses Medusa&rsquo;s severed head in order to turn him into stone &ldquo;&ldquo;Mine host,&rdquo; said Perseus, &ldquo;if the renown of noble birth is what impresses you, why, I&rsquo;m the son of Jove! If mighty deeds are what you marvel at, marvel at mine! | seek both hospitality and rest.&rdquo; (874-78) &ldquo;A time will come when your bright golden tree will be despoiled, Atlas; and the spoils will go to one who styles himself the son of Jove&rdquo; (880-82)&rdquo; Are you worthy of worship simply because of the life that you were born into?
Has immense agricultural wealth
Builds a fence around his orchards
Perseus is not willing to take this insult, pulls out medusas (even though she is dead) head and turns the giant into stone
This is how we get the idea of atlas holding up the Earth Flies off again and goes around the world after defeat of medusa
&ldquo;Ammon had condemned Andromeda (the one unjust, the other innocent) to pay the price for her own mother&rsquo;s speech. (918-20) the sea erupted with the roar of a great beast who rose up as he breasted the wide water. (943-45) so Perseus, through the resistless air swoops and dives at the monster from behind, and plunges his sword right up to the hilt into the shoulder of the raging beast. (979-82)&rdquo;
The great beast is the kraken
Perseus and Medusa# &ldquo;Now tell us, gallant Perseus, how strength and cleverness let you lay hands upon that head whose hair is woven through with snakes. (1050-52) a place beneath frigid Mount Atlas, guarded by its bulk, within whose entryway two sisters live, daughters of Phorcys, who shared a single eye: while one was passing it off to the other, her pass was intercepted by our hero.&rdquo;
&ldquo;he came at last to where the Gorgon lived. And everywhere, in fields, along the roads, he witnessed the sad forms of men and beasts no more themselves, but changed now into stone, misfortunates, who&rsquo;d glimpsed Medusa once. (1062-66) He too once looked upon her image, but it had been reflected in the shield of bronze our hero bore in his left hand; and while sleep held Medusa and her snakes, he struck her head off; from their mother&rsquo;s blood sprang swift Pegasus and his brother both. (1068-73)&rdquo;
Old ladies share a single eye that is passed between them Medusa slayed in her sleep Portrayed in clash of the titans Book 6# Summary# Arachne challenges Minerva to a challenge of ingenuity Athena is disguised Arachne is much better than Minerva who is outraged at being outclassed- she strikes Minverva Arachne hangs herself, but Minerva feels bad so transforms her into a spider Arachne&rsquo;s fate makes the people revere the gods Tereus (tyrant from thrace) enters narrative Liberates Athens from barbarians Tereus sets sail for Athens to fetch Philomela- lust grips him Weaves a portal Procne and Philomela tell Tereus that he has eaten his son-Tereus goes mad Of Praise and Punishment# Who is worthy of praise and what social position, social standing, or outright divinity have to do with it?
How does ovid think through social class even as he thinks through relationships between the human and divine
Where is justice in these stories? Is justice ever served or is this merely as cycle of violence?
&ldquo;Minerva has been judging storytelling contests. &ldquo;To praise is insufficient,&rdquo; she reflected; &ldquo;we will be praised—and we will not permit those who belittle our divinity to go unpunished!&rdquo; (4-7)&rdquo;
&ldquo;who (it was said) accepted praise that set her above the goddess in the art of weaving, a girl renowned not for her place of birth nor for her family, but for her art: her father, ldmon, came from Colophon, and (like the mother that Arachne lost) was of plebeian origin, a tradesman who steeped the thirst wool in purple dye. (9-16) They came not just to see the finished product, but to watch her working, for such comeliness and grace were present when she plied her art (24-26)&rdquo;
**Arachne is cocky- **brags about her own skill and ticks off Minerva (Athena)
Minerva reveals herself as Arachne brags Arachne is not terrified although the others around her are Will not back down
&gt; &quot;&quot;Let her compete with me, and if she winsI'll pay whatever penalty she sets!&quot;(36-37)Pallas [Athena/Minerva] disguises herself as a crone:puts on a wig of counterfeit gray hairand, with a staff to proper her tottering limbs,begins to speak...(38-41)Heed my advice: seek all the fame you wishas best of mortal weavers, but admitthe goddess as your superior in skill.(43-45)&quot;Although the gods are immortal, they are shown to be more animalistic, not really thinking etc.
&ldquo;Not Envy could have faulted this; Pallas did not, yet, bitterly resenting her rival&rsquo;s success, the goddess warrior ripped it, with its convincing evidence of celestial misconduct, all asunder; and with her shuttle of Cytorian boxwood, struck at Arachne&rsquo;s face repeatedly! She could not bear this, the ill-omened girl, and bravely fixed a noose around her throat; while she was hanging, Pallas, stirred to mercy, lifter her up and said: &ldquo;Though you will hang, you must indeed live on, you wicked child: So that future will be no less fearful than your present is, may the same punishment remain in place for you and yours forever!&rdquo; (183-197)&rdquo;
Niobe# &ldquo;Before her wedding day, when she was living in Maeonia, Niobe knew this girl; nevertheless, the punishment her countrywoman suffered did not convince Niobe to defer to the immortals, and to treat with them as with superiors. (212-18) &ldquo;What madness is this,&rdquo; she said, &ldquo;to prefer gods that you&rsquo;ve only heard of to the ones you&rsquo;ve actually seen? Why cultivate Latona&rsquo;s altars and deny me mine? (247-50)&rdquo;
&ldquo;Before her wedding day, when she was living in Maeonia, Niobe knew this girl; nevertheless, the punishment her countrywoman suffered did not convince Niobe to defer to the immortals, and to treat with them as with superiors. (212-18) &ldquo;What madness is this,&rdquo; she said, &ldquo;to prefer gods that you&rsquo;ve only heard of to the ones you&rsquo;ve actually seen? Why cultivate Latona&rsquo;s altars and deny me mine? (247-50)&rdquo;
&ldquo;&ldquo;Then dare prefer Latona&rsquo;s cult to mine, that daughter of the Titan Coeus, whoever he&rsquo;s supposed to be! (274-76) He gave her a place, unstable though it was, where she became the parent of—just two! One seventh of the yield of our womb! Blessed am I (who ever would deny it?), and (who can doubt it?) blessed will I be forever, safely kept by my abundance. Fortune would find me far too great to harm: though she took many, I&rsquo;d have many more. (284-301)&rdquo;
&ldquo;Seething with indignation at this treatment, Latona, on the summit of Mount Cynthus, addressed her children, the immortal twins: &ldquo;Just look at this, now! l, a goddess who gives way to no one else, except for Juno, and proud of having borne the pair of you [Phoebus/Apollo and Phoebe], now find my divinity in doubt! (302-8) Here as he wheeled his steed round in a circle, forcing the bit against its jaws, Ismenus, the earliest burden of his mother&rsquo;s [Niobe&rsquo;s] womb, cried out, &ldquo;Ah, me!&rdquo; as the arrow pierced his breast and the reins slid between his lifeless fingers. (328-32)&rdquo;
&ldquo;But who is the victor? In my wretchedness I still have far more children left to me than you in all your bliss! Thus, even after so many deaths, I am the victor still!&rdquo; (406-9) And as she prayed, the one for whom she prayed fell dead, the last of them; and now bereft, she sits, surrounded by the lifeless bodies of her sons, her daughters, and her husband, she sits there stilly, rigid in her grief. (430-34).&rdquo;
Latona# &ldquo;The Titan&rsquo;s daughter came to them, and knelt at the lake&rsquo;s margin for a cooling drink; the rustic mob forbade her. (493-95) And who would not be won over by such winning words? But they, despite her pleas, continued to restrain her, threatening to do her harm unless she goes away. (514-17) Anger put off thirst, for the Titan&rsquo;s daughter now would no longer beg unworthily, nor could she bear not speaking as a goddess. Turning her palms up to the stars, she cried, &ldquo;Dwell in this pond of your forevermore!&rdquo; (523-27) they all avort in ponds and mucky bogs, after their transformation into—frogs. (544-45)&rdquo;
Tereus, Procne, and Philomela# Tereus (King of Thrace) marries Progne (daughter of Pandion-king of Athens)
Falls in love with her sister Philomela (has sex with her)
Cuts her tongue to prevent her from telling her sister- but is still able to communicate by weaving story onto cloth
&ldquo;Neighboring nobles assembled, and nearby cities encouraged their kings to pay condolence calls [for the death of Amphion, Niobe&rsquo;s husband] (590-91) Who would believe that only you, Athens, did nothing? Warfare kept you from your duty, for a barbaric horde from overseas had marched its terror right up to your walls. Tereus of Thrace had raised that siege with his auxiliaries, had driven off the foe, And now was famous for his victory. And since he was a man of wealth and power, and a descendant of the god of war, King Pandion had bonded with Tereus by joining him in marriage to his daughter, Procne. (601-12)&rdquo;
&ldquo;Five autumns passed, then Procne coaxed her husband with these words: &ldquo;If I am at all pleasing in your sight, then either let me visit with my sister or let her visit with me&rdquo; (630-34)
When he first saw her, Tereus caught fire as instantly as ripe grain or dry leaves, or as hay stored in a barn goes up in blazes. (654-66)
he said this was merely Procne&rsquo;s wish, and added tears, as though they too were part of his commission. By the gods above, what utter blindness dwells in human hearts! (674-77)
Nevertheless, if the gods are watching this, if heavenly power means anything at all, If, with my honor, all has not been lost, somehow or other I will punish you; I&rsquo;ll cast aside my modesty and speak of what you&rsquo;ve done; if I escape this place, I&rsquo;ll go among the people with my tale. (781-87) And after these outrages, he returned to Procne, who at sight of him inquired about her sister. Tereus replied with practiced sobs and a convincing tale of how she died—a story that his tears made altogether credible. (812-17) he takes her tongue instead. (799) And yet from suffering comes native wit, and often cleverness is born of misery. Upon her loom, she hangs a Thracian web and starts to weave threads of deep purple on a white background, depicting the crime. (829-34)&rdquo;
He is like Apollo and Daphne-driven by insatiable lust
&ldquo;While Procne was still speaking to her sister, Itys came to his mother, who at once realized what she could do, and said, taking him in with her unfeeling eyes, &ldquo;How very like his father the boy is!&rdquo; she turned to look upon her sister&rsquo;s face, and then turned back and forth between them, wildly. (897-901, 912-13) How can it be that this one calls me mother, while that one cannot call me sister? (916-17)&rdquo;
&ldquo;Now Tereus, all unaware, receives an invitation to attend a feast which his wife falsely claims to be a rite of the Athenians: husbands only may partake of it; all slaves are sent away and all attendants: Tereus dines alone (937-42) Procne is unable to hide her savage joy; and eager now to be the bearer of misfortune cries, &ldquo;The one that you are seeking is within!&rdquo; (947-50) One flies off to the woods, the other finds her refuge under roofs. he turns into a stiffly crested bird with a huge beak in place of his long sword: the hoopoe, which seems armed as though for war. (968-69, 975-77)&rdquo;
Book 8# To Consider# What does it mean to be impious What is the role of family in these works How do passions affect the bonds of kinship? Is there justice or just violence? Summary# Minos attacks Alcathous, ruled by Nisus
Scylla falls in love with Minos Scalps father to give power to Minos Dedalous Maze to conceal the Minotaur Icarus flies to close to the sun Thesus&rsquo;s victory over the minitour causes his fame to spread Meleager kills his uncles over a dispute over the spoils of a hunt Stories of men who did not have regard to the gods and suffered the consequences Nisus and Scylla# Meanwhile, along Megara&rsquo;s coast, King Minos was pillaging, and trying out his forces against its capital, now held by Nisus, who had, among the venerable locks of gray upon his head, a tuft of purple, which guaranteed the safety of his realm. (7-12) she knew Europa&rsquo;s son the best of all, the countenance of Minos being more familiar to her than it should have been. (27-29)
In peacetime, Scylla, daughter of King Nisus, would often come and toss a pebble here. (20-21) As she set gazing at his tents, she said &ldquo;What should I feel about this dreadful war? (52-53)
and certainly he wages a just war Of retribution for his murdered son [Androgeous, killed under mysterious circumstances in Athens] ; his motive will prevail, as will the arms advancing it. I think that we are lost. (72-75) Much better would it to be for him to conquer us without delay, without exterminating our folk or being hurt himself. (78-81)
the daughter slips silently into her father&rsquo;s chambers and robs him of his fated lock. (112-14) I surrender myself, my nation, and my gods as well, and seek no other recompense but you; receive this pledge that guarantees my love, this purple lock—which is no lock at all, but my father&rsquo;s head! (121-26) Her father, hovering on yellow wings (for he had just been changed into an osprey), caught sight of her and dove to the attack. Feathers appear upon her hands; transformed into a bird, she is now known as Ciris, and has this name from the clipped lock of hair. (197-99, 204-6)
Minos and Adriane# The scandal of his family had grown past all concealment; not the mother&rsquo;s [Pasiphae] foul adultery was proven by the strange form of the Minotaur, half man, half bull. Minos determined to remove the cause of this opprobrium from his abode, enclosing it within a labyrinth devised and built by Daedalus. (212-19)
Minos confined the monstrous form within the labyrinth, and twice it had been fed on the blood of sacrificed Athenians; after another nine-year interval, the third demand for tribute doomed the creature, when, by the aid of Princess Ariadne, the path back to the hidden entranceway, which none before had ever reached again, was rediscovered when the thread was wound; then Theseus abducted Minos&rsquo; daughter and sailed to Dia, where he cruelly abandoned his companion to her wailing. (233-35)
Assume that most readers already know the story
Meanwhile, detesting Crete and his long exile, and longing to return to his own nation, Daedalus found that an escape by sea was closed to him. (252-54) Icarus, his boy, was standing close by, unaware of any danger in the things he handled; he smiled as he snatched at wisps of feathers blown from his father&rsquo;s workbench by a passing breeze, or left a thumbprint in the golden wax and playfully got in his father&rsquo;s way. (269-75)
And as he works and as he warns the boy, the old man&rsquo;s cheeks are dampened by his tears; the father&rsquo;s hands are trembling as he gives his son a not-to-be-repeated kiss, and lifts off on his wings into the air. (291-95) Some fisherman whose line jerks with his catch, some idle shepherd leaning on his crook, some plowman at his plow, looks up and sees something astonishing, and thinks them gods, who have the power to pass through the air. (303-7)
Daedalus and Perdix# As he entombs his child&rsquo;s pathetic corpse, he is observed from where a rank ditch drips, by a chatty partridge, who chirps cheerfully and makes his wing tips flutter in applause (328-31) Daedalus envied him, and headlong hurled this lad of precepts from a precipice (348-49)
Impious Acts and Exemplary lives# What does it mean to be &ldquo;impious&rdquo;? Consider the role of family in these stories. How do the passions witnessed in these tales affect the bonds of kinship? Where is justice in these stories? Is there ever justice or merely a cycle of violence?
